Joe,<br>
     Can't say that I saw any racism personally during 3 1/2 years in the Army.  The only times I heard of incidents between black and white soldiers was while stationed at Fort Carson from Aug '69 to Jul '71 after returning from Vietnam. <br><br>
     The perception that Blacks were dying in large numbers probably was due to the fact that most Black casualties whether officer or enlisted were infantry.  Infantry deaths were often seen by quite a few people.  The war in the air with the fighters was much different, one or two witnesses , if any.  And most Air Force and Naval Aviation casualties were white; as there were not many black pilots at that time.  The POW/MIA list, which is heavily weighted with pilots, is mostly white.  As for percentages, removing white aviation casualties should bring up the Black percentage up a point, but probably not much more.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


